Gemini: You should NOT be committing these files to your Git repository. The .terraform directory and its contents are usually generated and should be ignored.

Here's how to fix this:

Add .terraform to your .gitignore file:

If you don't have a .gitignore file in the root of your repository, create one now (in the C:\ai-execution-system directory).

Open the .gitignore file in a text editor and add this line:

.terraform
Save the .gitignore file. This tells Git to ignore the entire .terraform directory.

Stage the .gitignore file:

C:\ai-execution-system>git add .gitignore
Commit the .gitignore file:

C:\ai-execution-system>git commit -m "Add .gitignore to ignore .terraform directory"
Remove the large files from Git's cache: This is important to remove the already tracked large files from your Git repository.

C:\ai-execution-system>git rm --cached -r deployment/terraform/.terraform
Commit the removal of the large files:

C:\ai-execution-system>git commit -m "Remove .terraform directory from repository (ignore with .gitignore)"
Try pushing again:

C:\ai-execution-system>git push
Explanation:

We added .terraform to .gitignore so Git will ignore this directory in the future.
We used git rm --cached to remove the already tracked .terraform directory from Git's history without deleting the local files.
By committing these changes and then pushing, you will push the .gitignore rule and the removal of the large files, but not the large files themselves.
After these steps, the git push should be successful because the large files will be excluded.

Let me know if you have any issues with these steps! After this push is successful, we are finally done!
